INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES (194,2,'2011-04-29 15:45:59','2011-04-29 15:45:59','Only French anthropologist Claude Levi Strauss, swallowed in the green of South America, could fathom the local tribe of Amazonians that I have encountered, smoking cigarettes, sporting sailor tattoos and standing akimbo six feet atop a pair of roller blades. It is palpable, these girls are abrasive and elusive and they go by the name of Bloody Barracudas, one of the island’s up-and-coming derby teams. Riding havoc on wheels, the girls from the metropolitan area team are aiming to bring the fast-paced contact sports from the skating rink into the streets of the Caribbean.\r\n\r\nFormed around mid-February, the Barracudas have been fomenting alternate athleticism in the metropolitan area ever since, with a side of snarling bite and sweetened smiles of course. “This is a cooperative,” says Ivonne Cardona, transgender coach of the furious femmes “ we started this ourselves, 100 per cent form the ground up.” Though the girls participated in a previous team, management was too mechanical, too strict and too focused on the image of derby and not derby itself. “We didn’t appreciate having to train on the clock like it was a job. It stopped being about the sport and that’s when it stopped being fun” says team player Kristen Fink. They split the scene and pooled their brains, brawn and beauty and started recruiting players for their own league, and before they knew it, dame after dame lined up to sign up (so much so that there were enough players to form a second team, the Smoking Diablas.) Though its an independent endeavor, the team nonetheless some help from Moisty  Skate Park and are open to sponsoring. The Barracudas are currently prepping up to meet the Women’s Flat Track Derby Association requirements for inscription to finally be considered “official” (the nationwide league, like the NBA, sans spousal abuse).\r\n\r\nThough some players had some experience rolling before joining the team, most had to go through a baptism-by-fire type crash course, falling down many a times, but inevitably getting back up as their unofficial team motto exclaims “accept and modify.” Cardona mentioned that training is relentless for these self-proclaimed “guerillera warfare derby rollers”, but refused to disclose any training tips, on the basis of panoptic paranoia I could only imagine, or taste. “We eat terror for breakfast and derby for dinner” exclaims Cardona, an emblazoned testament to the team’s professional (at an amateur level) athleticism and work ethic. More importantly though, some ground rules.\r\n\r\nRoller derby consists two teams racing against themselves in an elliptical skating track, with no more than five players each, on roller skates (granted)  at any given time. Playing teams consist of four blockers and one jammer (sporting a rambunctious starred helmet to demarcate their role), the scoring player. A team scores a point whenever their jammer passes the adversary in a lap (one point per lap), but of course, the obtrusive blockers will remain faithful to their monikers and prevent any point-based lollygagging of any sort by pushing or hitting, known as “checking” . That whole interlude is called a “jam” and it lasts about two minutes or roughly the same amount of time as Donald Trump’s Saturday night. Rinse, wash and repeat for two 30-minute periods and the team with most points wins, in a nutshell.\r\n\r\nIntrigued by the whole notion of a “Thunderdome” –esque blood sport, I headed over to rival team Smoking Diablas’ coach, Nandy Morales for more information on its history, and learning goes way back, more than I imagined. “It  started in the 1920’s as race derby, not so much a sport but more of spectacle,” says Morales, hair pomade-slick, a teddy boy in some distant time perhaps. He went on to say that the sport went down hill from then on and it wasn’t until the 90’s that a revival was taking place in Austin,  TX.. Spurred by do-it-yourself work ethic, punk ideology, and feminism, the sport has been garnishing rabid followers willing to combine show(wo)manship and athleticism with a dash of 1950’s retro rockabilly cropped fringes and Betty Page-inspired attire.\r\n\r\nThough a school teacher, nurse, architect and lawyer might not necessarily have a lot in common in the day time, they come together when the night comes creeping in little cat feet and start working on something bigger than themselves. They foster a sense of kinship through this signifying ritual of the people and the gathering. “It’s not just a sport”, says Bloody Barracuda Krizia Díaz, “it’s an alternative for every girl out there that doesn’t feel like she fits in any particular sport, this is her sport,” future plans consists of integrating youth teams as wellIt’s not just about creating a subculture, but also about giving pack to a wider community. Not just fire-engine lipstick and pencil skirts, the feminist discourse is clear in its inception, substance is style. Though from the outside it seems like a typical male fantasy-scenario (stop the clocks, violence in hot pants?), at its core, derby is a sport of empowerment. Juxtaposing themselves in the traditionally patriarchal activity of the contact sport is a way of breaking down established structures. Blocker Yaitza Alvarez, “As a woman, I have to put everything I got out there, constantly pushing.”\r\n\r\nAs a kicker, I asked these femmes whether or not Drew Barrymore’s 2009 film <em>Whip It</em> (a movie about the sport) had any influence on their project and I was quickly answered in a harmony of scoffs. I take it as a no.\r\n\r\nFierce, brutal, communal, revitalizing and reinvigorating,  roller derby might be the second wind that will bring together disparate youth subcultures into a unifying ritual and the positive outlet for the female community fosters sexual equality in a time where domestic-abuse and misogyny boil over as symptoms of a spiritual crisis. Though these girls might easily drink any dandy under table or grind my bones to make their bread, there is still something slightly magical when they glide around with aplomb. It’s not grace, and certainly not the hot pants, but maybe, it’s an uncomplicated sense of fun that we all inevitably strive for, fun which involves all of us as a community.\r\n\r\nExhibition matches are predicted in the near future but for now, the Bloody Barracudas will make their official premier at their debutante ball dubbed  “Pin-Up Party Roller Derby Edition” (sponsored by Coors Light) this Friday night at the Vatican (Jordan St., Santurce). For more information on the sport and team, log into their Facebook page or contact the team at <a href=\"mailto:bloodybarracudas@gmail.com\" target=\"_blank\">bloodybarracudas@gmail.com</a>\r\n\r\nOriginally published April 28 on the Puerto Rico Daily Sun','Havoc on wheels: the Bloody Barracudas and the rise of roller derby','Hot pants, sailor tattoos and derby. Freudian traumatic fantasy or just plain fun?','publish','open','open','','havoc-on-wheels-the-bloody-barracudas-and-the-rise-of-roller-derby','','','2011-04-29 15:45:59','2011-04-29 15:45:59','',0,'http://modernaddendum.com/?p=194',0,'post','',0),(164,2,'2011-03-19 21:14:53','2011-03-19 21:14:53','Two things have disappointed me: myself and The Strokes much anticipated album <em>Angles</em>, released on RCA/Rough Trade records. After a 5 year recording hiatus, the band has risen out of their soporific lounging but sadly, the gunk has yet to clear from their eyes, preventing them from making any good decisions.  The record gets a heavy-duty makeover unlike past releases, moving away from the hip-shaking aesthetic that fans have come to know and love towards a more electronic-based sound. This time around, singer Julian Casablancas has relinquished his dictatorial position as the head honcho songwriter to his band chums, democratizing the recording process but as the album shows, the sum of its parts is not necessarily greater than the whole.\r\n\r\nAh, but I digress. The record kicks off with “Machu Picchu”, a revving analog whistle before busting out a pop-ish reggae rhythm with dual slap-back echoing guitars and digitalized drumming, setting the 80’s heavy sound which the band (for reasons unknown) has decided to adopt. . Seemingly inoffensive, the track quickly shifts into second gear with a furious mondo-distorto axe barrage, off-setting the pre-established notion of a dance floor money-maker hit machine. This album might actually be great, one thinks (at least the first part is.)\r\n\r\n“Under Cover of Darkness” is a delectable classic Strokes cut (and arguably the album’s best track), chock-stuffed with hooks, swings and licks. The intro features harmonizing Thin Lizzy-ish lead guitars before warming up to the recognizable Casablancas melodic croons backed up by jangley chords, rock n’ roll grit riffage and unprecocious upbeat drumming. “Two Kinds of Happy” is a drive through The Cars-inspired verse with a detonating rambunctious chorus that vacuums all noise out of the passage to placidly return to the verse newly again while “Taken For a Fool” rips apart the lingering verse formations with the blisteringly infectious chorus and a frantic guitar exercises coupled with funky bass lines. Sadly, all good things must come to an end as “You’re So Right” suggests: a moronic Radiohead rip-off that its only saving grace is Nick Valensi and Albert Hammond Jr.’s fretwork.\r\n\r\nWhen the album opened with the lines “I’m putting your patience to the test”, it was referring to the second part of the album: a disappointing, and pointless, anthology of forgettable tracks lacking any memorable groove. “Games” features an obscenely cheesy synth intro and depressingly lame programmed hand claps while “Call Me Back” is bossa-nova chanteur track that never comes. What’s worse is that the track actually sports some interesting hooks but it quickly takes a turn for the boring. The band shifted from the newly-found confidence of the album’s first part to the uncomfortable jive that is “Gratisfaction” with a forced faux-anthemic chorus that is tad reminiscent of “Someday” except for, you know, the good parts. The prog-heavy “Metabolism” is truly un-exciting and un-imaginative but, thankfully, their closer “Life is Simple in the Moonlight” doesn’t completely suck if it wasn’t for some intriguing soloing and analog effects.\r\n\r\nProduction-wise the album has abandoned their borderline lo-fi recording techniques of their outstanding 2001 <em>Is This It?</em> and 2003’s <em>Room on Fire</em>, saying sayonara to their supposedly “garage” rhetoric and embracing synth Britannia (a questionable love life decision) and swathing the whole record with an analog electric haze which is pretty difficult to sober up from (as the cover demonstrates, the band has been quaffing massive amounts of neon and synth). While vocals ring out with clarity, the bass has oomphs and the guitars are subjected to various sonic effects, the drums might come off sometimes as flat and tacky. Overall, the bright and pop-oriented sound is offset by the electric textures of post-production Though the whole band had a hand at production and arranging (as well as Gus Osberg and Joe Chicarelli) the album sounds more like <em>Phrazes For the Young II</em> than <em>First Impressions of Earth</em>\r\n\r\nLyrically, the band is unadventurous, eschewing significant others for their misgivings “You get taken all the time for a fool all the time and I don’t know why” as well as any logical order of the weekly structure: “Monday and Tuesday are my weekend.” (“Taken For a Fool”). Faux-angst lingers and malingers every once in a while, as seen in “Games”: “Living in an empty world…” as well as their classic “I don’t really like your girlfriends, baby” discourse as seen in “Under Cover of Darkness”: “And I’m tired of all your friends/ Listening at your door.”\r\n\r\nThe truth of the matter is that <em>Angles</em> is not really a bad album, the correct nomenclature would be “ok”. The first part is catchy and a tad daring, but tragically, the latter is just exceedingly forgettable (which pains everyone since singles like “Under Cover of Darkness” embody a plurality of sonic voices and overall goodness). It’s even more disappointing to think that all of the members have recorded some pretty interesting stuff (Fabrizio Moretti’s Little Joy, Hammond Jr. and Casablanca’s solo efforts and even Nikolai Fraiture’s Nickel Eye is intriguing at times) but the end result is just not as good as it was expected from such a high-profile group. There is still space for vindication in the near future; The Strokes might still be able to put out an album that sounds as though they actually wanted to make.\r\n\r\nOriginally published March 19, 2011 on <a href=\"http://blogcritics.org/music/article/music-review-the-strokes-angles1/\">Blogcritics.org</a>','The Strokes study the geometry of average with \"Angles\"','Adios hip-shaking hooks, hello droll synths. ','publish','open','open','','the-strokes-study-the-geometry-of-average-with-angles','','','2011-03-19 21:15:47','2011-03-19 21:15:47','',0,'http://modernaddendum.com/?p=164',0,'post','',0),(2,2,'2011-01-11 00:24:08','2011-01-11 00:24:08','Dandy, deacadent, bon vivant or bouffant, Enrique Olivares the II, Esq.  possesses a B.A. in English and lives in Guaynabo. He doesn\'t know which is worse. He likes rock n\' roll and this humble servant has endeavored to meticulously write about it. He writes for a Puerto Rican newspaper titled the Daily Sun, concerning matters lofty, fashionable a