quality control” (any band could upload their rattle and hum) and the sometimes the deviation into shoddy artwork and assembly. The main difficulty is that local releases have limited their digital packaging to rudimentary aspects such as cover sleeve and maybe lyrics and have yet to expand features (much like Radiohead did their 2009 free downloadable single “These AreMy Twisted Words” which incorporated fascinating ASCII art panels among other tidbits.) One should not decry that bands with digital releases are merely partaking in shabby productions, these groups are merely accommodating to the times.\r\n\r\nBut at the gist of it, since audio quality is a creative and economic control which the band <a href=\"http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/fantasmes.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-73 alignright\" title=\"fantasmes\" src=\"http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/fantasmes-300x277.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"277\" /></a>is solely responsible for, concrete format holds scissor that will the unmake the Gordian knot. The metaphysics of the experience are fundamental for appreciation: the act of unwrapping, popping it in and listening are held by the narrative structure of creating an immersive experience that  is a dialectic between the listener, the object of aesthetic knowledge which  is the “real” record (whether it be 12’’ or 12 cm) , and the band itself, something which doesn’t necessarily translate to listening music on the go (iPod or in a car) or engaging it mechanically via a person to computer listening session (not “dissing” this experience of course.)\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/similar.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-77 alignleft\" title=\"similar\" src=\"http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/similar-300x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a>\r\n\r\nIt would be interesting to see a more inclusive and expansive record/data experience, such as online exclusive added bonuses á la Director’s Cut,  beside the digital download bonus option which is a staple for both CD and vinyl releases nowadays (the 7’’ “Spooky Fools” being one of those). Though concrete format seems to be going down in sales (thanks to internet piracy which none of us listeners partake, ahem) and everything now is digested in itty-bitty data fun-sized chunks, people will probably continue getting their literal hands on their favorite tracks for a while. The times have certainly changed (as well as the rules of the game) it’s reassuring that there are still dedicated enough aural art devotees hanging around, and they are making it their task that music gets out, ensuring that people have options like they deserve to.\r\n\r\nOriginally published Feb. 12, 2010 in the <a href=\"http://www.prdailysun.com/index.php?page=news.article&amp;id=1297525196\" target=\"_blank\">Puerto Rico Daily Sun</a>','Local music\'s contemporary conundrum: digital vs. physical format. ','','inherit','open','open','','72-revision-24','','','2011-02-12 18:42:34','2011-02-12 18:42:34','',72,'http://modernaddendum.com/2011/02/72-revision-24/',0,'revision','',0),(109,1,'2011-02-12 18:42:51','2011-02-12 18:42:51','Scene: you waltz into your locally owned bookstore in search for a text that might pique your interest and find that a couple of your favorite local bands have released their latest sonic concoction on luscious slabs of glassy black paste and silvery-smooth CDs. When you get home, you read on the internet that yet another local group has cut a record and you can download it for free. What’s going on? Groups are currently spewing audio warble through every viable medium, both inside and outside the island. Digital data or concrete compact discs and records?\r\n\r\nThe contemporary debate has limited its spectrum of vision to quarrelling and squabbling over whether or not vinyl format is making is becoming the new “in” thing (and subsequently taki