e a gray suit met with a checked blue shirt encourages a livelier  companion for the stroll about town romp (patterned accessories go well  with solids while a solid pocket garment provides support for the more  daring main events.) Also, mix and match tie and square texture: a silk  tie should be accompanied by a dry   handkerchief (cotton or  foulard work exceptionally well)while thicker looking neckwear should go hand <a href=\"http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/whimsey.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-151\" title=\"whimsey\" src=\"http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/whimsey-222x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"222\" height=\"300\" /></a>in hand with a silken, or wet garment as does dandy Lord Breaulove Whimsy with a puffed green garment.\r\n\r\nThe  manifold possibilities of squares and peaks featured in the breast  pockets of past tall, dark and handsomes are a testament of how  individuals give their own personal twist to a long-standing classic.  Cary Grant irregularly angled his to give a little bite to his attire  while Fred Astaire puffed his to complement his entertainment pomp.  Though the thought of folding one’s own handkerchief might send men  scrounging for the hills, this seemingly daunting feat is actually quite  simple to accomplish. The internet provides illustrative guides to the  process while your local dapper dandy is more than willing to guide you  through the ordeal. The magic of folding and placing the handkerchief is  making sure it is not angular and mathematical (since it demonstrates  angularity and constriction) and that it points towards your shoulder and not inward. The biggest faux-pas a man could commit  would be to over-emphasize the hanky by making it bulbous and intrusive  for it detracts attention from the face and the attire. When purchasing a  handkerchief, make sure it does not bulge in the pocket (style sage  Alan Flusser suggests a range between 16 and 18 inch. Square).\r\n\r\