 the pioneers of Latin jazz, the late, great American trumpet player Dizzy Gillespie and Cuban percussionist Chano Pozo, this is the 21<sup>st</sup> installment of the concert series, and now that the event is all grown up and legal, it’s come with party favors that will blast the bones off its audience members.\r\n\r\nThursday’s first set was taken over by percussionist Richie Flores and his sextet. Brooklyn, born but raised in Puerto Rico, Flores has been pounding the skins since he was 5, first playing with Roberto Roena, Grupo Batacumbele and Apollo Sound at the tender age of 8, but soon becoming an artist-in-demand, playing for greats such as Tito Puente, The Fania All Stars and Gato Barbieri. Mixing jazz with rap, and even salsa, Flores has been creating a different musical experience throughout the years.\r\n\r\nDubbed the “fastest hands of the east and west” by Latin Beat Magazine, it is easy to see why after a slightly pudgy, and slightly short, man of modest appearance pulls up next to a set of congas and starts the show by wailing on them at supersonic machine-speed, rolling from drum to drum in split seconds. He was Eddie Palmieri one moment, and Keith Moon of the timbales the other, with such a sense of velocity. The brass section of Mike Rodríguez and Iván Renta on trumpet and saxophone, respectively, kept up with the conga shuffle, trading off soaring scale progressions which both bellow and cut through the mix of John Benítez’s walking bass lines and chords and Robby Ameen’s wall of sound drumming. Pianist Elio Villafranca contested the percussion runs with Joe Zawinul-inspired keyboarding. Most compositions were infused with Latin-lingo jazz licks as well as a classical appreciation of a big band and swing aesthetic as their piece “Latin Lovers” with singer Marfil Delgado demonstrates. The sextet also played a rendition of the folkloric “Cortaron a Elena” (“They Stabbed Elena”), a prog-plena  which fluctuates between mad time changes, going from the intriguing 7/4 to the standard 4/4 to the bizarre 4/7 in a matter of seconds.\r\n\r\nIf Flores’ set was a furious drive through local sounds and jazz, then Monty Alexander’s Harlem Kingston Express’ tended more to the loftier and laid-back. Born in Jamaica, Alexander began as a pianist with local ska groups (one of which, the Skatalites, went to back up, say, Bob Marley) in his native Jamaica before moving the U.S., where he did session work with the likes of Frank Sinatra, Oscar Peterson and Dizzy himself. Combining the exciting American and rustic sounds of his geographical moniker, Alexander brought a particular and unique brand of jazz to the fray.\r\n\r\nAlexander started the latter part of the evening with an interpretation of ol’ Blue Eyes’ staple “Come Fly With Me”, grazing the white ivory of his piano with grace and aplomb, quickly gauging the composition into a light footed exchange with drummer Obed Calvaire and upright bass-player Hassan Shakur. The group rode through some melodic numbers with seemingly effortless dynamicity but the show started to shift its paradigm once percussionist Bobby Thomas entered the arena, toying with the hand drums, adding an air of mischief but the whole paradigm changed when the rest of the Express joined the musical debate. The group interpreted a mellower version of the orientalist standart “Caravan”, with a minor Caribbean feel to it. Parting from such classic set in local terms, what followed was a full blown dub number that would have “Scratch” Perry skanking to the lower register of the emanating sounds. The group went on to play a jazz/reggae fusion rendition of Marley’s “No Woman No Cry”,which had the audience humming to its motif, and the classic “Concrete Jungle”. It was fascinating seeing one half of the band run through jazz standards while the other half counterbalances the equation with dexterous musical craftsmanship and pop. Guitarist Wendel Ferraro skanked and ripped through songs with pentatonic licks while electric bassist Courtney Panton and 2<sup>nd</sup> drummer Bobby Thomas eased the rhythmic plane. Keyboardist Earl Appleton also dished out spacey Steel Pulse synths that tied the dubs nicely.\r\n\r\nWhat’s truly captivating is Alexander’s adroitness and personality whether it be switching between piano and melodica or chatting up with the audience. He can go from Debussy-like dreamy arpeggios as he did in “Strawberry Hill” or he could pull out all the pop stops as with the closer “Love Notes”, but more importantly, he is a performer, springing up from the seat at times like a coiled-up Art Tatum with a Little Richard coif.\r\n\r\nIt’s entrancing to hear disparate and grappling music, especially since it’s from the Caribbean, a common ground between the repeating islands that we inhabit. Jazz then becomes the unifying string thread of the Sargasso archipelago, grasping salsa and reggae in its way, bringing different cultures together through the primal ceremonial communion of music. The evening was filled with an array of moments that stood out of each performance, memorable and enticing. Gillespie said: “I don’t care much about music. What I like is sounds”, and baby, the Heineken JazzFest sure does promise a lot of it.\r\n\r\nOriginally published in the Puerto Rico Daily Sun on June 4, 2011.','The Heineken JazzFest Pt. 1','Heineken JazzFest starts grooving on a good note.','publish','open','open','','heineken-jazzfest-starts-grooving-on-a-good-note','','','2011-06-06 03:43:27','2011-06-06 03:43:27','',0,'http://modernaddendum.com/?p=205',0,'post','',0),(195,2,'2011-04-29 15:39:47','2011-04-29 15:39:47','','barracudas','','inherit','open','open','','barracudas','','','2011-04-29 15:39:47','2011-04-29 15:39:47','',194,'http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/barracudas.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(196,2,'2011-04-29 15:30:02','2011-04-29 15:30:02','Only French anthropologist Claude Levi Strauss, swallowed in the green of South America, could fathom the local tribe of Amazonians that I have encountered, smoking cigarettes, sporting sailor tattoos and standing akimbo six feet atop a pair of roller blades. It is palpable, these girls are abrasive and elusive and they go by the name of Bloody Barracudas, one of the island’s up-and-coming derby teams. Riding havoc on wheels, the girls from the metropolitan area team are aiming to bring the fast-paced contact sports from the skating rink into the streets of the Caribbean.\n\nFormed around mid-February, the Barracudas have been fomenting alternate athleticism in the metropolitan area ever since, with a side of snarling bite and sweetened smiles of course. “This is a cooperative,” says Ivonne Cardona, transgender coach of the furious femmes “ we started this ourselves, 100 per cent form the ground up.” Though the girls participated in a previous team, management was too mechanical, too strict and too focused on the image of derby and not derby itself. “We didn’t appreciate having to train on the clock like it was a job. It stopped being about the sport and that’s when it stopped being fun” says team player Kristen Fink. They split the scene and pooled their brains, brawn and beauty and started recruiting players for their own league, and before they knew it, dame after dame lined up to sign up (so much so that there were enough players to form a second team, the Smoking Diablas.) Though its an independent endeavor, the team nonetheless some help from Moisty  Skate Park and are open to sponsoring. The Barracudas are currently prepping up to meet the Women’s Flat Track Derby Association requirements for inscription to finally be considered “official” (the nationwide league, like the NBA, sans spousal abuse).\n\nThough some players had some experience rolling before joining the team, most had to go through a baptism-by-fire type crash course, falling down many a times, but inevitably getting back up as their unofficial team motto exclaims “accept and modify.” Cardona mentioned that training is relentless for these self-proclaimed “guerillera warfare derby rollers”, but refused to disclose any training tips, on the basis of panoptic paranoia I could only imagine, or taste. “We eat terror for breakfast and derby for dinner” exclaims Cardona, an emblazoned testament to the team’s professional (at an amateur level) athleticism and work ethic. More importantly though, some ground rules.\n\nRoller derby consists two teams racing against themselves in an elliptical skating track, with no more than five players each, on roller skates (granted)  at any given time. Playing teams consist of four blockers and one jammer (sporting a rambunctious starred helmet to demarcate their role), the scoring player. A team scores a point whenever their jammer passes the adversary in a lap (one point per lap), but of course, the obtrusive blockers will remain faithful to their monikers and prevent any point-based lollygagging of any sort by pushing or hitting, known as “checking” . That whole interlude is called a “jam” and it lasts about two minutes or roughly the same amount of time as Donald Trump’s Saturday night. Rinse, wash and repeat for two 30-minute periods and the team with most points wins, in a nutshell.\n\nIntrigued by the whole notion of a “Thunderdome” –esque blood sport, I headed over to rival team Smoking Diablas’ coach, Nandy Morales for more information on its history, and learning goes way back, more than I imagined. “It  started in the 1920’s as race derby, not so much a sport but more of spectacle,” says Morales, hair pomade-slick, a teddy boy in some distant time perhaps. He went on to say that the sport went down hill from then on and it wasn’t until the 90’s that a revival was taking place in Austin,  TX.. Spurred by do-it-yourself work ethic, punk ideology, and feminism, the sport has been garnishing rabid followers willing to combine show(wo)manship and athleticism with a dash of 1950’s retro rockabilly cropped fringes and Betty Page-inspired attire.\n\nThough a school teacher, nurse, architect and lawyer might not necessarily have a lot in common in the day time, they come together when the night comes creeping in little cat feet and start working on something bigger than themselves. They foster a sense of kinship through this signifying ritual of the people and the gathering. “It’s not just a sport”, says Bloody Barracuda Krizia Díaz, “it’s an alternative for every girl out there that doesn’t feel like she fits in any particular sport, this is her sport,” future plans consists of integrating youth teams as wellIt’s not just about creating a subculture, but also about giving pack to a wider community. Not just fire-engine lipstick and pencil skirts, the feminist discourse is clear in its inception, substance is style. Though from the outside it seems like a typical male fantasy-scenario (stop the clocks, violence in hot pants?), at its core, derby is a sport of empowerment. Juxtaposing themselves in the traditionally patriarchal activity of the contact sport is a way of breaking down established structures. Blocker Yaitza Alvarez, “As a woman, I have to put everything I got out there, constantly pushing.”\n\nAs a kicker, I asked these femmes whether or not Drew Barrymore’s 2009 film <em>Whip It</em> (a movie about the sport) had any influence on their project and I was quickly answered in a harmony of scoffs. I take it as a no.\n\nFierce, brutal, communal, revitalizing and reinvigorating,  roller derby might be the second wind that will bring together disparate youth subcultures into a unifying ritual and the positive outlet for the female community fosters sexual equality in a time where domestic-abuse and misogyny boil over as symptoms of a spiritual crisis. Though these girls might easily drink any dandy under table or grind my bones to make their bread, there is still something slightly magical when they glide around with aplomb. It’s not grace, and certainly not the hot pants, but maybe, it’s an uncomplicated sense of fun that we all inevitably strive for, fun which involves all of us as a community.\n\nExhibition matches are predicted in the near future but for now, the Bloody Barracudas will make their official premier at their debutante ball dubbed  “Pin-Up Party Roller Derby Edition” (sponsored by Coors Light) this Friday night at the Vatican (Jordan St., Santurce). For more information on the sport and team, log into their Facebook page or contact the team at <a href=\"mailto:bloodybarracudas@gmail.com\" target=\"_blank\">bloodybarracudas@gmail.com</a>','Havoc on wheels: the Bloody Barracudas and the rise of roller derby','','inherit','open','open','','194-revision','','','2011-04-29 15:30:02','2011-04-29 15:30:02','',194,'http://modernaddendum.com/2011/04/194-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(197,2,'2011-04-29 15:43:01','2011-04-29 15:43:01','Only French anthropologist Claude Levi Strauss, swallowed in the green of South America, could fathom the local tribe of Amazonians that I have encountered, smoking cigarettes, sporting sailor tattoos and standing akimbo six feet atop a pair of roller blades. It is palpable, these girls are abrasive and elusive and they go by the name of Bloody Barracudas, one of the island’s up-and-coming derby teams. Riding havoc on wheels, the girls from the metropolitan area team are aiming to bring the fast-paced contact sports from the skating rink into the streets of the Caribbean.\r\n\r\nFormed around mid-February, the Barracudas have been fomenting alternate athleticism in the metropolitan area ever since, with a side of snarling bite and sweetened smiles of course. “This is a cooperative,” says Ivonne Cardona, transgender coach of the furious femmes “ we started this ourselves, 100 per cent form the ground up.” Though the girls participated in a previous team, management was too mechanical, too strict and too focused on the image of derby and not derby itself. “We didn’t appreciate having to train on the