t</sup> installment of the concert series, and now that the event is all grown up and legal, it’s come with party favors that will blast the bones off its audience members.\n\nThursday’s first set was taken over by percussionist Richie Flores and his sextet. Brooklyn, born but raised in Puerto Rico, Flores has been pounding the skins since he was 5, first playing with Roberto Roena, Grupo Batacumbele and Apollo Sound at the tender age of 8, but soon becoming an artist-in-demand, playing for greats such as Tito Puente, The Fania All Stars and Gato Barbieri. Mixing jazz with rap, and even salsa, Flores has been creating a different musical experience throughout the years.\n\nDubbed the “fastest hands of the east and west” by Latin Beat Magazine, it is easy to see why after a slightly pudgy, and slightly short, man of modest appearance pulls up next to a set of congas and starts the show by wailing on them at supersonic machine-speed, rolling from drum to drum in split seconds. He was Eddie Palmieri one moment, and Keith Moon of the timbales the other, with such a sense of velocity. The brass section of Mike Rodríguez and Iván Renta on trumpet and saxophone, respectively, kept up with the conga shuffle, trading off soaring scale progressions which both bellow and cut through the mix of John Benítez’s walking bass lines and chords and Robby Ameen’s wall of sound drumming. Pianist Elio Villafranca contested the percussion runs with Joe Zawinul-inspired keyboarding. Most compositions were infused with Latin-lingo jazz licks as well as a classical appreciation of a big band and swing aesthetic as their piece “Latin Lovers” with singer Marfil Delgado demonstrates. The sextet also played a rendition of the folkloric “Cortaron a Elena” (“They Stabbed Elena”), a prog-plena  which fluctuates between mad time changes, going from the intriguing 7/4 to the standard 4/4 to the bizarre 4/7 in a matter of seconds.\n\nIf Flores’ set was a furious drive through local sounds and jazz, then Monty Alexander’s Harlem Kingston Express’ tended more to the loftier and laid-back. Born in Jamaica, Alexander began as a pianist with local ska groups (one of which, the Skatalites, went to back up, say, Bob Marley) in his native Jamaica before moving the U.S., where he did session work with the likes of Frank Sinatra, Oscar Peterson and Dizzy himself. Combining the exciting American and rustic sounds of his geographical moniker, Alexander brought a particular and unique brand of jazz to the fray.\n\nAlexander started the latter part of the evening with an interpretation of ol’ Blue Eyes’ staple “Come Fly With Me”, grazing the white ivory of his piano with grace and aplomb, quickly gauging the composition into a light footed exchange with drummer Obed Calvaire and upright bass-player Hassan Shakur. The group rode through some melodic numbers with seemingly effortless dynamicity but the show started to shift its paradigm once percussionist Bobby Thomas entered the arena, toying with the hand drums, adding an air of mischief but the whole paradigm changed when the rest of the Express joined the musical debate. The group interpreted a mellower version of the orientalist standart “Caravan”, with a minor Caribbean feel to it. Parting from such classic set in local terms, what followed was a full blown dub number that would have “Scratch” Perry skanking to the lower register of the emanating sounds. The group went on to play a jazz/reggae fusion rendition of Marley’s “No Woman No Cry”,which had the audience humming to its motif, and the classic “Concrete Jungle”. It was fascinating seeing one half of the band run through jazz standards while the other half counterbalances the equation with dexterous musical craftsmanship and pop. Guitarist Wendel Ferraro skanked and ripped through songs with pentatonic licks while electric bassist Courtney Panton and 2<sup>nd</sup> drummer Bobby Thomas eased the rhythmic plane. Keyboardist Earl Appleton also dished out spacey Steel Pulse synths that tied the dubs nicely.\n\nWhat’s truly captivating is Alexander’s adroitness and personality whether it be switching between piano and melodica or chatting up with the audience. He can go from Debussy-like dreamy arpeggios as he did in “Strawberry Hill” or he could pull out all the pop stops as with the closer “Love Notes”, but more importantly, he is a performer, springing up from the seat at times like a coiled-up Art Tatum with a Little Richard coif.\n\nIt’s entrancing to hear disparate and grappling music, especially since it’s from the Caribbean, a common ground between the repeating islands that we inhabit. Jazz then becomes the unifying string thread of the Sargasso archipelago, grasping salsa and reggae in its way, bringing different cultures together through the primal ceremonial communion of music. The evening was filled with an array of moments that stood out of each performance, memorable and enticing. Gillespie said: “I don’t care much about music. What I like is sounds”, and baby, the Heineken JazzFest sure does promise a lot of it.','Heineken JazzFest starts grooving on a good note.','','inherit','open','open','','205-revision','','','2011-06-06 03:38:08','2011-06-06 03:38:08','',205,'http://modernaddendum.com/2011/06/205-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(208,2,'2011-06-06 03:43:09','2011-06-06 03:43:09','Thursday\n\nPork pie hats, black rimmed shades, lawn chairs and a crowd of beautiful people tailgating the parking lot: the awful London weather that’s invaded the island is also threatening to rain of these things but the people don’t seem to care. They’re here for one thing and one thing only: jazz, and a lot of it.\n\nThe Heineken JazzFest kicked off last Thursday at the Tito Puente Amphitheater to the sounds of brass, drums, strings and euphonious pianos. Spanning four days, up until Sunday, the festival will be presenting a myriad of jazz voices that blend American, European and Caribbean soundscapes into a sustained plateau of harmonies. Dedicated to the pioneers of Latin jazz, the late, great American trumpet player Dizzy Gillespie and Cuban percussionist Chano Pozo, this is the 21<sup>st</sup> installment of the concert series, and now that the event is all grown up and legal, it’s come with party favors that will blast the bones off its audience members.\n\nThursday’s first set was taken over by percussionist Richie Flores and his sextet. Brooklyn, born but raised in Puerto Rico, Flores has been pounding the skins since he was 5, first playing with Roberto Roena, Grupo Batacumbele and Apollo Sound at the tender age of 8, but soon becoming an artist-in-demand, playing for greats such as Tito Puente, The Fania All Stars and Gato Barbieri. Mixing jazz with rap, and even salsa, Flores has been creating a different musical experience throughout the years.\n\nDubbed the “fastest hands of the east and west” by Latin Beat Magazine, it is easy to see why after a slightly pudgy, and slightly short, man of modest appearance pulls up next to a set of congas and starts the show by wailing on them at supersonic machine-speed, rolling from drum to drum in split seconds. He was Eddie Palmieri one moment, and Keith Moon of the timbales the other, with such a sense of velocity. The brass section of Mike Rodríguez and Iván Renta on trumpet and saxophone, respectively, kept up with the conga shuffle, trading off soaring scale progressions which both bellow and cut through the mix of John Benítez’s walking bass lines and chords and Robby Ameen’s wall of sound drumming. Pianist Elio Villafranca contested the percussion runs with Joe Zawinul-inspired keyboarding. Most compositions were infused with Latin-lingo jazz licks as well as a classical appreciation of a big band and swing aesthetic as their piece “Latin Lovers” with singer Marfil Delgado demonstrates. The sextet also played a rendition of the folkloric “Cortaron a Elena” (“They Stabbed Elena”), a prog-plena  which fluctuates between mad time changes, going from the intriguing 7/4 to the standard 4/4 to the bizarre 4/7 in a matter of seconds.\n\nIf Flores’ set was a furious drive through local sounds and jazz, then Monty Alexander’s Harlem Kingston Express’ tended more to the loftier and laid-back. Born in Jamaica, Alexander began as a pianist with local ska groups (one of which, the Skatalites, went to back up, say, Bob Marley) in his native Jamaica before moving the U.S., where he did session work with the likes of Frank Sinatra, Oscar Peterson and Dizzy himself. Combining the exciting American and rustic sounds of his geographical moniker, Alexander brought a particular and unique brand of jazz to the fray.\n\nAlexander started the latter part of the evening with an interpretation of ol’ Blue Eyes’ staple “Come Fly With Me”, grazing the white ivory of his piano with grace and aplomb, quickly gauging the composition into a light footed exchange with drummer Obed Calvaire and upright bass-player Hassan Shakur. The group rode through some melodic numbers with seemingly effortless dynamicity but the show started to shift its paradigm once percussionist Bobby Thomas entered the arena, toying with the hand drums, adding an air of mischief but the whole paradigm changed when the rest of the Express joined the musical debate. The group interpreted a mellower version of the orientalist standart “Caravan”, with a minor Caribbean feel to it. Parting from such classic set in local terms, what followed was a full blown dub number that would have “Scratch” Perry skanking to the lower register of the emanating sounds. The group went on to play a jazz/reggae fusion rendition of Marley’s “No Woman No Cry”,which had the audience humming to its motif, and the classic “Concrete Jungle”. It was fascinating seeing one half of the band run through jazz standards while the other half counterbalances the equation with dexterous musical craftsmanship and pop. Guitarist Wendel Ferraro skanked and ripped through songs with pentatonic licks while electric bassist Courtney Panton and 2<sup>nd</sup> drummer Bobby Thomas eased the rhythmic plane. Keyboardist Earl Appleton also dished out spacey Steel Pulse synths that tied the dubs nicely.\n\nWhat’s truly captivating is Alexander’s adroitness and personality whether it be switching between piano and melodica or chatting up with the audience. He can go from Debussy-like dreamy arpeggios as he did in “Strawberry Hill” or he could pull out all the pop stops as with the closer “Love Notes”, but more importantly, he is a performer, springing up from the seat at times like a coiled-up Art Tatum with a Little Richard coif.\n\nIt’s entrancing to hear disparate and grappling music, especially since it’s from the Caribbean, a common ground between the repeating islands that we inhabit. Jazz then becomes the unifying string thread of the Sargasso archipelago, grasping salsa and reggae in its way, bringing different cultures together through the primal ceremonial communion of music. The evening was filled with an array of moments that stood out of each performance, memorable and enticing. Gillespie said: “I don’t care much about music. What I like is sounds”, and baby, the Heineken JazzFest sure does promise a lot of it.\n\nOriginally published in the Puerto Rico Daily Sun on June 4, 2011.','The Heineken JazzFest Pt. 1','Heineken JazzFest starts grooving on a good note.','inherit','open','open','','205-autosave','','','2011-06-06 03:43:09','2011-06-06 03:43:09','',205,'http://modernaddendum.com/2011/06/205-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(209,2,'2011-06-06 03:42:03','2011-06-06 03:42:03','Pork pie hats, black rimmed shades, lawn chairs and a crowd of beautiful people tailgating the parking lot: the awful London weather that’s invaded the island is also threatening to rain of these things but the people don’t seem to care. They’re here for one thing and one thing only: jazz, and a lot of it.\r\n\r\nThe Heineken JazzFest kicked off last Thursday at the Tito Puente Amphi