the group’s debut performance, and the audience was luck enough to be regaled with their music and performance.\n\nHarris initiated the show with a jagged vibraphone melody that was backed up by drummer and native Henry Cole and bassist Luques Curtis with an ultra-tight driving punch but suddenly turned into phrasing madness once Scott and Sánchez doubled the melodic motif and lead into ravenous improvisation. Performers at heart, the bandleaders juggled soloing duties but also limelighted pianist Luis Perdomo’s light-fingered touch and counter-pointed sense of harmony as well as percussionist Eddy Mauricio Herrera’s hand drum rolls.\n\nNinety Miles is the distance between Cuba and Florida’s lowest-reaching point and the group’s music reflects the geographical and latitudinal qualities of the music: grounded in the Latin and Caribbean rhythms of Sánchez’s Sargasso Sea as well as the New Orleans spirit of which Harris and Scott hail from. Their music is forceful yet mollififed by the mystic and chiming euphony of Harris’ vibraphone and the wind section is anchored in long phrasing. With influences raging from Davis to Zappa, the ensemble also grooved with the dream-like with their composition “Los Olividad” (“The Forgotten”), an in memoriam for those wrecked by Katrina and left awashed in the rain. Though the clouds stopped barking and started biting with swaths of rain, the band maintained focus, jovial and energetic throughout their set, rearranging instruments in the face of aqueous adversity.\n\nThe final set could only be mete with an explosive bang  and Humberto Ramírez and his appropriately named Big Band indeed did provide. The Yerba Buena house band has been serving up boogaloo with a side of jazz every Monday for the past 2 yours and orchestrated a tightwound tribute set dedicated to jazz legends Tito Puente and timbalero extraordinaire, singer and bandleader Tito Rodríguez, chanteuse La Lupe and ‘ol Blue Eyes himself, Frank Sinatra. The rambunctious ensemble cruised through Fania favorites such as Puente’s “Complicación” and Rodríguez’s “Avisale a mi contrario” sung by invitee Josué Rosado as well as tearjerkers and heartbreakers such as La Lupe’s “La tirana” as well as the saucier “Fever”, performed by Michelle Brava. Though Sinatra’s swing  might have seemed a bit at odds with mambo jazz, NJ singer Mike Ritacco graced numbers such as “I’ve Got You Under My Skin” and “My Way” fitted in nicely with the rest of the repertoire. With the frenetic beat, the audience could not but dance in the face of the ritualistic upheaval of the stage and the orchestra pushed the moment to its crisis with a tour de force rendition of Puente’s “Cuban Fantasy” with an encore of Sinatra’s “New York, New York” followed by spastic brass soloing and a wall of timbales-on-conga blasts set to Rodríguez’s “Mama Guela”\n\nThe Heineken JazzFest coalesced a series voices coming from different backgrounds: the Big Easy, the Big Apple, Havana and our own backyard and turned them into something palpable that it grabs you by the guts. The word eclectic gets thrown around much these days but pluralism is still pertinent in the island’s musical taste, and the festival sure did leave a good one at that. The night sky cleared up towards the end, just in time for when everyone realized that it the whole event as plainly speaking: it was great. For those who lived through Ninety Miles and all the great acts, and even those acts that didn’t play, it was memorable, energetic, amazing and all that jazz.','Heineken JazzFest Pt. 2','Ends not with a whimper, but with a bang. ','inherit','open','open','','210-autosave','','','2011-06-08 23:59:47','2011-06-08 23:59:47','',210,'http://modernaddendum.com/2011/06/210-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(216,2,'2011-06-08 23:58:42','2011-06-08 23:58:42','Fuck yeah Ninety Miles\r\n\r\nIrish poet and Nobel laureate W.B. Yeats wrote in “The Second Coming”:  “Things fall apart, the center cannot hold”, and thing certainly seeme