eir hard-knocking Peruvian punk forefathers Los Yorks by covering their raucous beat “Solo Pido Amor”\n\nThough it’s fairly easy to trace the genealogy of rock n’ roll through Los Vigilantes’ sound, ranging from swampy blues singles, the Nueva Ola and girly bubblegum all the way to South American and Spanish punk, the group’s sonic chutzpah is not a complete copping of their elder’s style. Tracks tend to oscillate between sugary-sweet bubblegum hooks such as the catchy wipeout number “Me Imagino” (with ex-guitarist Ricardo Villaró donning the power pop vocals) and full-blown Neanderthal agro-rock numbers such as “Letal”, with both poles gravitating towards solid melody-heavy singles of yesteryear. The driving chords of Pepe Carbadillo’s sets the driving rhythm of while Javier Garrote’s bouncing bass licks adds some color to the mix while Jorge “Jota” Mundo’s scorching fretwork and soloing flaunts blues grit, and while tracks threaten to collapse under its own dynamite weight and party-animal work ethic, Rafa Díaz’s drumming runs an ultra-tight, yet primitive, ship that keeps things vacuum-sealed. Splitting vocal duties three-ways, Garrote’s bassier growl and Carbadillo’s and Mundo’s higher register complement each other quite nicely, fostering a trifecta of back-up vocals, creating a fuller sound.\n\n<a href=\"http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/Vigis.jpg\">\n</a>Those looking for the mud-caked production of some modern trend-setting groups will be sorely disappointed. The album has to be one of the best sounding records from the island’s local catalog with its chiming mid-range and booming low end  punch, displaying a rare enthusiasm and dedication to the sound just as much as the structure and hook. Not to say that the record’s jangly and shiny mystique is indicative of a straight-laced attitude, added gain dirties the mix, balancing beauty with bite. The little details strewn about the album helps break up the monotony of the quartet ensemble, with a Stooges-like keyboard ring lurking in the background and the highlighting of an organ (courtesy of Giovanni DelaRosa) in the my-baby’s-a-pain twelve bar “A Ella”.\n\n&lt;iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/17972132?title=0&amp;amp;byline=0&amp;amp;portrait=0\" width=\"400\" height=\"225\" frameborder=\"0\"&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=\"http://vimeo.com/17972132\"&gt;LOS VIGILANTES - VEN VAMOS&lt;/a&gt; from &lt;a href=\"http://vimeo.com/user2379619\"&gt;PURO VICIO&lt;/a&gt; on &lt;a href=\"http://vimeo.com\"&gt;Vimeo&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;\n\nThough the album comes on as a frantic and satanic caveman-rock dance-a-thon, non-greaser types and despisers of fun might be turned off by the way it plays. Instead of a solid chunk of music with a narrative or cohesive line, the record feels like a collection of singles, albeit hip-shaking good-time singles. Structurally, it might get tedious since most tracks follow a standard verse-chorus-verse, twelve bar or ballad forms of rock n’ roll and pop records, but arrangements keep it lively and interesting.\n\nLos Vigilantes’ self-titled LP is guaranteed to keep spinning on every record creep’s turntable this summer, guaranteeing a myriad of groovy, hip-gyrating, grab-a-cold-one-and-gyrate-what-your-momma-gave-ya all-night ground-shaking dance luau. With is ringed dual fists cover threatening to bruise its listeners and its flip-side monstrous caricature of the members (by Chaveli Sifre Riestra and “Juni” Figueroa respectively), the record is a heavenly slice of brutal rock n’ roll.  It is always reinvigorating seeing local groups going back and scavenging through the annals of Puerto Rico’s rich, yet often occluded, Nueva Ola and rock n’ roll singles catalog and their choice of singing in Spanish in an English-dominated music market proves that the boys want to follow up on that legacy.   With modern rock journalism squabbling over whether or not the newest band is lo-fi enough to be garnered the ideological “garage” tag, Los Vigilantes is a welcome act that combines the best of all possible worlds, because in the end, it all sounds like good rock n’ roll to me.\n\nLos Vigilantes will be releasing their self-titled record this Thursday at Nuestro Son in Old San Juan alongside Las Ardillas. The album will be available in both CD and Vinyl format.\n\n<a href=\"http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/Vigis.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-235\" title=\"Vigis\" src=\"http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/Vigis.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"576\" height=\"384\" /></a>','Los Vigilantes and their non-stop joy ride into the outlawed heart of rock n’ roll','Local greasers all lubed up with their latest hip-shaking extravaganza. ','inherit','open','open','','234-autosave','','','2011-07-06 00:38:56','2011-07-06 00:38:56','',234,'http://modernaddendum.com/2011/07/234-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(239,2,'2011-07-06 00:37:48','2011-07-06 00:37:48','The needle drops and the opening riff of “Ven, Vamos” starts jangling, introducing a familiar melody from some brighter, half-remembered life that buoys with an uncomplicated sense of fun, adventure, youth and a dash of frustration and melancholy. Such is the ethos and sound of local greasers Los Vigilantes’ self-titled, full-length debut on Slovenly records. Already experienced in the vinyl arts with thesir “Mi Mami Dijo/Que Mal” ’45 single and a superb cover of the Rolling Stones’ “Paint it Black” on Norton records, the four-man ensemble steeps into higher ground with a 12 inch that promises to run away into the future while casting a lone eye back to the infinite heart of a lost age of pop, rock n’ roll and punk.\r\n\r\nFollowing the massive hooks of its opener, Side A is chock-full of brand-spanking-new tasty groovies such as the enfant terrible, delinquent beat-rock pout of “<em>Échame la Culpa” and the crooning garage wail of “Niña Donde Estás”. And while the “Tequila”-themed “La Chica” sports