l authentic and new: the disparate voices coalesce, sounds become woven, the snark hits your chest like a fistful of hammers.\r\n\r\nThough The Bee’s Knees are not quite the cat’s pajamas with the EP, they are well on their way at paving they’re own aural mishaps, but perhaps they’re music reveals much more than it does at face value. The fractured and urgent sentiment and production should not be confused with amateurism, but with still-teenage pangs. The music captures opaque, yet jem-like gut feeling of putting it something out there. Youth is wasted on the young, and as such getting wasted at elaborating something concrete out of something ephemeral transcends the tyranny of utter boredom. Seeing these cats playing in different band (perennial babyfaced Cristian Zayas in Naranja and the mustachioed Ivan Moreira in Codex), brings to mind continual process, a steady fluxus between bodies. Though many, borne away like salt into the sea, disappear, other regenerate, other come to table gear head lingo and acryclic jargon at will. There are no circles, no drafted parameters, the only subculture there is of youth: irresponsible  And that edge-of-the-seat feeling, that impending something that seems to cut through every sonic artefact some one in this island puts out, is out there. The youth, the artist, miscreant, cretin, ne’er-do-well is uneasy, because they are waiting for something. They know it will happen. Things are happening all the time, but not the big one. Not yet the heavy star everyone slouches and works towards to. They know something will happen. They just don’t know how.','Wasted Youth: The Bee\'s Knees First EP','','inherit','open','open','','260-revision-5','','','2011-12-16 17:24:00','2011-12-16 17:24:00','',260,'http://modernaddendum.com/2011/12/260-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(268,1,'2011-06-09 16:45:59','2011-06-09 16:45:59','In the single “Modern Art,” bassist for the Black Lips, Jared Swilley, sings over a fuzzed out guitar: “K-hole at the Dalí/Seeing the unknown/Well it might have been a molly/‘Cause my mind’s being blown. Two things are clear about this band: 1) These hooligans quaff enough drugs that make Charlie Sheen look like he’s been huffing Elmer’s glue out of a brown bag. 2) Its music sounds just like they are: debauched, offensive and slightly criminal, all of which translates into its most recent vinyl pressing.\r\n\r\nFamed for its notorious stage antics, such as making out with each other, flinging piss and whipping out their peters as well as their (legally questionable) lifestyle choices, the boys have cleaned up their act for its latest release, <em>Arabia Mountain</em>, on Vice Records. Well, sort of.\r\n\r\nProduced by the band with the help of Mark Ronson and Deerhunter’s Lockett Pundt, the band’s sixth studio efforts veers towards a catchier, cleaner and somewhat sobered up sound from past releases, putting out song after song of hip-shaking garage goodness.\r\n\r\nThe album kicks off with “Family Tree,” a ditty featuring circus-like motif before switching into a cowpoke westernized groove with reverberating guitars before reverting to the furious yelping of its lead melody. Such a raucous becomes the band’s signature fast-ride through its amalgamation of tracks and central medium for communicating their psychedelic riffs that will boogie-woogie on everybody’s mind and spine. The rest of the album is a merry coalescence of machine-gun downstroke strumming punk guitar, some mild country chords and non-stop danceable garage beats.\r\n\r\nStripping it down to the skivvies, the Black Lips thrust rock n’ roll into the middle of the cold night and start playing grab-ass for around 42 minutes. “Noc-A-Homa,” an elegy for the Atlanta Braves’ slightly un-PC mascot, is a hard hitting and sultry number about the insalubrious behavior of the hard-partying “tribe of one.” Good ol’ fashion hip-shaking music is what pours from the record, and lots of it.\r\n\r\nProduction has cleared up from the days of mind-warbling psychedelia of <em>200 Million Thousand</em>. It would seem that Ronson, of ‘ol Dirty Bastard and Amy Winehouse production fame, is ill-fated to ill-suit the band’s rock n’ roll ideological agenda but his mixing touch does not compromise the ouvre. Effects such as fuzz and reverb make appearances but do not go rampant in the record, while the guitar/bass/drum ensemble does not deviate from the staple codes. Ian St. Pé’s guitar assumes the lead melody, while Cole Alexander’s keeps the rhythm, which are both backed by the low end of Jared Swilley’s slightly melodic bass playing and Joe Bradley’s percussion.\r\n\r\nThough some crystal clear production is found in the album, as is “Spidey’s Curse,” a twee-pop-inspired shaker about almost-raped superheroes, the band’s lo-fi roots of <em>Let It Bloom</em> and <em>Black Lips!</em> are found in their New   York Dolls-esque “Dumpster Dive.” Pundt’s contribution in “Bicentennial Man” reveals a subtle robotic tremolo on the vocals along with the driving rhythm upholding everything.\r\n\r\nOrchestration, though not necessarily lush and full, does breach out and incorporates some interesting tidbits, including a theremin on “Modern Art” (courtesy of Sean Lennon), saxes on the irresponsibly alcoholic “Mad Dog” and opening track, as well as a whistling musical saw in the moronic Ramones-inspired track “Raw Meat.” Also, it\'s unclear if the “human skull” played by Alexander was used for musical purposes or for plain ‘ol satanic rituals. The division of songwriting and singing labors between Alexander, Bradley and Swilley provides a satisfying sense of variety as well as a healthy plurality of voices.\r\n\r\nThe Lips’ sound and aesthetic in the record vacillates between feel good party anthems and drug-idolizing numbers; its main internal conflict, is its <em>agon</em> in a sort of way. The former sports such infectious grooves as their singles “Go Out and Get It,” the self-esteem boosting, self-help summer jingle with jangly arrangements, and “New Direction,” a driving surfy beat of sugary bubblegum leanings that’s a surefire floor-stomper. “Don’t Mess With My Baby” follows that same aesthetic with its Johnny Marr opening riffing juxtaposed in a Bo Diddley hand jive, pouting about how your baby keeps smoking all your dope.\r\n\r\nThe latter category is slightly more hermetic and darker, with tracks such as “Mr. Driver,” a stoned-out-of-my-mind cruise through dissonance and swaths of fuzzed out guitars that oscillate between the enigmatic lines, “I want to bleed on my squire” and the irreverent “My pecker’s long.” The sinister “The Lie,” perhaps the album’s choicest cut, is a gloom and doom number akin to a more nefarious psychedelic folk tradition, a Jefferson Airplane-meets-Black Sabbath affair, thanks to the haunting fretwork and chilling vocal lines, as well as freak out guitar mutilated solos. The album’s closer, “You Keep On Running” is a dirgy, swampy, slimy and reverb-caked march through a ghostly collection of hash haze, floating organs and phantasmal wailing.\r\n\r\nAt the core, the album cranks out 16 delectable nuggets of rock n’roll but most songs are just more of the same Lips-fare. They move towards a new direction with their slightly more enigmatic and polemic tracks but are at odds with their classic repertoire. It’s not to say most songs lack some indescribable kernel of pleasure. Au contraire, they’re solid compositions. What the group lacks in dexterous musicality. It more than make up for it with superb songwriting.\r\n\r\nThe Black Lips have shown with its latest release that they are mature enough to crank out a steady array of tracks that prove that they are as good as its stage antics. Not necessarily a work of staggering beauty and might, <em>Arabia Mountain</em> is definitely a rock n’ roll safari that will blast the bad bones off your body and keep you grooving \'til you turn black and blue. It’s not terribly complex, but it’s terribly fun, and that’s what rock n’ roll should be.\r\n\r\nOriginally Published June 9 on <a href=\"http://blogcritics.org/music/article/music-review-black-lips-arabia-mountain/\">blogcritics.org</a>','Black Lips\' \"Arabia Mountain\"','The boys are loud, debauched,lewd, irreverent and slightly criminal, just like their sound. ','inherit','open','open','','218-revision-2','','','2011-06-09 16:45:59','2011-06-09 16:45:59','',218,'http://modernaddendum.com/2011/06/218-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(275,2,'2012-03-30 18:51:52','2012-03-30 18:51:52','The  Museo de Arte de Ponce has its own particular way of ushering spring. Instead of the gem-like brightness the trinitaria’s red and violet, the museum has given way to somber and celestial ochres and cochineal with their latest exhibition, “Del Greco al Goya: Obras maestros del Museo del Prado” (“From El Greco to Goya: Masterpieces of the Museo del Prado ”). As the title indicates, the exhibitions comprises 25 paintings generously lent by the Spanish cultural institution coursing over 200 years of painting history from the 16<sup>th</sup> century up to late 18<sup>th </sup>century, regaling the island crowd with both royal portraiture and biblical episodes.\r\n\r\nSave for a selection of still lives, these two aesthetics are the dominating curatorial narratives. Though this dichotomy seems to dictate a strict split, it is but feigned binary for both styles blur the demarcation. Domenikos Theotokopoulos’ (alias El Greco) agonizing “San Sebastian,” with its fractured and eloganted corps, stretching heavenwards, despite its transcendental yearnings, can be studied as an exercise in portraiture while Velazquez’s “Retratos orantes de Felipe IV y Mariana de Austria” (“Philip IV in Prayer &amp; Mariana de Austria, Queen of Spain, in Prayer”) translates the fervent Catholicism of scripture scenes into the royal context. The book-end artists of the exhibition, El Greco and Goya (his Ferdinand VII and Tadea Arias de Enríquez portraits are unsettling as much as they are captivating), as well as artists in between, provide a thorough presentation of Spain’s “Siglo de Oro,” as well as its devotion to the counter-reformation, but the preeminence of the namesakes, as well as the promotional “Storm und Drang,” might detract attention from non-Spanish tableaux and painters. It is perhaps these paintings, the ones the eye might at times omit, that need to be engaged most intensely for their sublimity and form.\r\n\r\nAs careless as the eye is, it can also be as rigorous as the gaze with which we approach art, and no better painting in the exhibition confirms the vitality of the optical engagement than Titian’s (Tiziano Vecellio)  “Salome.” If popular depictions of the femme fatale render her consumed in the decadence of the dance, Titian’s interpretation is that of balancing restraint.  Her gaze is not an invitation into the scene’s sensuousness but rather an interruption of it: her eyes look outside of the rapture her body is given to. The eroticism suggested by the theme (the low cut dress, her hair hung with jewels) is assuaged by its construction. It is not detail or the balanced earthy palette which entrances us, but her glance, one that distances the viewer from the scene; it is not what we see, but from where we see that consumes our aesthetic pleasures, and the confrontation between subject and art is exterior to its oils. In this sense, the painting is akin to an exercise in portraiture rather than a biblical episode in which we ballot our interpretation. John the Baptist’s head fades into shadows just as her flowing mantle, stripping the figure from its form, leaving an enduring gaze, meeting ours as violently as the saint’s fate.\r\n\r\nMoving from the exchange of glances to the scrutiny of them, Peter Paul Rubens’ “La Sagrada Familia con Santa Ana” ( “The Holy Family with Saint Anne”) is as beautiful as it is difficult to study outside of its obvious theme. Though the Dutch master’s renowned supreme adroitness in color and form draws us in, it is near impossible to divert the gaze from the ardent Catholicism manifest in the scene. The child-god and goddess encase an economy which we cannot participate if only for strict adoration. While Byzantine and medieval dyad depicts the son looking up at the mother while she looks at us, working as a celestial intermediary between the divine and the human, the Ruben’s dyad is exclusive: his hand upon her ashen breast, her hand lifting the porcelain foot, only Saint Anne’s light caress suggests only small incorporation. If the hierarchy of grace is limited to the godly, it is Saint Joseph which provides the point of entry for the human. His gaze of unbending intensity reveals the basic phenomenological quality of existence, the ability to contemplate. Saint Joseph’s amazement is a response to the presence of the transcendental, not strictly in the sense of the divine, but in terms of the lofty and gorgeously sublime.\r\n\r\nIf truth, according to Plato, is irresistible, so is beauty. It is through the refinement of our optical abilities which allow us to fully approach, with a new found vigor and pleasure, that which arouses the deepest human yearnings and pleasures, not only art, but everything as well. Though beauty is not impossible to find, the Museo de Arte de Ponce and Museo del Prado have definitely made it more convenient for us.\r\n\r\n“Del Greco a Goya” will run from March 25 to July 9. The Museo de Arte de Ponce is located in Las Americas Ave. and is open Wed-Mon. from 10 a.m. to 6 p.m.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','The Ecstasies of the Eye: A Second Look at \"Del Greco al Goya.\"','','publish','open','open','','the-ecstasies-of-the-eye-a-second-look-at-del-greco-al-goya','','','2012-04-27 17:18:08','2012-04-27 17:18:08','',0,'http://modernaddendum.com/?p=275',0,'post','',0),(270,1,'2012-03-06 02:51:48','2012-03-06 02:51:48','','Contact form 1','','publish','open','open','','contact-form-1','','','2012-03-06 02:51:48','2012-03-06 02:51:48','',0,'http://modernaddendum.com/wpcf7_contact_form/contact-form-1/',0,'wpcf7_contact_form','',0),(271,2,'2012-03-13 03:28:14','2012-03-13 03:28:14','Perception is a mosaic: a wash of stench, sight, and sound beaten into a one impression. Who can tell the foam of the sky from the ring of the wind or the scent of white echoes from the tones of the saffron sun? Reception is a rough chaos, and as wine sifted through a clump of fingers, the taken gives way to the irrevocably lost. Though the cloud is too heavy to grasp, there is still something fixed that situates its axis. Among the hot barricades of green, a looming scarlet yearns under its intensity, inviting an intenser look: the ghosts of the Cruz de Malta.\r\n\r\nThe baptism of blood does not correlate the thing, the flower, to its reality, the spoken name. In the tropics, confused among chrysanthemums for the Turkish delight of Siberian origin, our bushel of beauty is not the European Cruz de Malta (<em>Lychnis chalcedonica</em>) of similar hue but doubled on its count of four. <em>Ixiora coccinea, </em>the <em>vrai</em> nomenclature, which we have donned upon our boutonnières as well as our backyards is a descendant of the geranium genus rooted from the parallel climates of Ind and blue airs of the Mediterranean (which allow such a splendid creation to thrive as an infinite Summer blessing in Spring, Fall and Winter in this island) and often hailed in a myriad of brutal nommes which us in the Caribbean rarely hear: <em>llama del bosque, geranio de la jungla</em>. The flower is the compass of a secret language sequestered from our tongues. Names for such strange creatures borrowed from stranger tongues: too far to grasp, yet close enough to see.\r\n\r\nBut what is it that one sees? To tower at five and half feet only to direct our eyes at a bush of red or yellow flowers, copious to a point of inconspicuousness that to the untrained eye might prove boring. Leaves fat, petals oblong, smell unfelt. For the mind in lust of something visceral, it is the equivalent of moving through the D’Orsay with the lights turned off. But it is precisely this that chars the <em>coccinea</em> into the slab of our brains. The rose, as Burne-Jones gazed at it with its hue of crimson and fumes of dreams and songs, overwhelms the reader: too much of sensations drowning us in its decadent cusp. The Cruz de Malta, on the other hand, forces us, not to see, but to see again. It is not a mess of tiny flowers, but a fistful of vigor, multiplied unto itself.\r\n\r\nIn the amber afternoon, the crimson and jaune dissipate into the winking eye of the Sun-god but in the torrential afterbirth of the tropical rain, the flower retains its self-same brutality. We confuse the consistency of its form with its <em>ennui</em>, funneling into despise. As a child, I loathed the flower: every garden and yard I played in had it. I studied it as an exercise in horticultural laziness and lack of imagination verging on pornography: the whore of Babylon sports the slut of flowers. It was not until the refinement of vision, and not taste, that I understood that the flower’s beauty is revealed to us by its iconic fidelity: we see the same color, same hue and same tonalities regardless of place, position or politics and yet we cast it out of our gaze for its repetition in expression. We’ve been beckoned, and we’ve turned the eye away. Quoting Pater: “colour is no mere delightful quality of natural things, but a spirit upon them by which they become expressive to the spirit” ( 42, <em>The Reinassance: Studies in Poetry and Art</em>). What is expressive to the spirit is its invitation to gaze and when one accepts the feat of it, to collapse time and senses so one can strain the eye at the marvel of its plenty, it is when one truly sees its blossoming kernel of sublimity, both for the <em>jouissance</em> of looking as well as for the development of looking. As per Wilde in “The Decay of Lying” enunciates : “One does not see anything until one sees its beauty.”\r\n\r\nRunning,  in an attempt to shake off the haze of an evening of hash, I had crossed a neighboring home with a particular bush of the <em>coccinea</em>: a group that seemed to be of a peculiar pale pink. Upon closer inspection, the true color was in fact the standard crimson, save for the fact that it was an imperfect bloom: a flower not meant to grow but meant to die. Such harrow and such gorgeousity were balanced perfectly on an instance of vitality cast against doom.  But only through the trials of close seeing could I have suffered and regained. It is time to recuperate our visions, not a time to let the eye go idle.  Perhaps it is our belief in angels that has veered our heads towards the heavens, expecting beauty to be celestial and ascendant that sometimes we forget to look down.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOriginally published at <a href=\"http://revistaxxi.com/?p=719\">Revista XXI</a>.  Follow up on the series!','The Dandy’s Metaphysical Guide: The Optics of the Cruz de Malta. ','Though the cloud is too heavy to grasp, there is still something fixed that situates its axis. Among the hot barricades of green, a looming scarlet yearns under its intensity, inviting an intenser look: the ghosts of the Cruz de Malta.\r\n\r\nThe baptism of blood does not correlate the thing, the flower, to its realit','publish','open','open','','the-dandys-metaphysical-guide-the-optics-of-the-cruz-de-malta','','','2012-03-13 03:28:14','2012-03-13 03:28:14','',0,'http://modernaddendum.com/?p=271',0,'post','',0),(272,2,'2012-03-13 03:23:22','2012-03-13 03:23:22','Perception is a mosaic: a wash of stench, sight, and sound beaten into a one impression. Who can tell the foam of the sky from the ring of the wind or the scent of white echoes from the tones of the saffron sun? Reception is a rough chaos, and as wine sifted through a clump of fingers, the taken gives way to the irrevocably lost. Though the cloud is too heavy to grasp, there is sti