 splendid creation to thrive as an infinite Summer blessing in Spring, Fall and Winter in this island) and often hailed in a myriad of brutal nommes which us in the Caribbean rarely hear: <em>llama del bosque, geranio de la jungla</em>. The flower is the compass of a secret language sequestered from our tongues. Names for such strange creatures borrowed from stranger tongues: too far to grasp, yet close enough to see.\n\nBut what is it that one sees? To tower at five and half feet only to direct our eyes at a bush of red or yellow flowers, copious to a point of inconspicuousness that to the untrained eye might prove boring. Leaves fat, petals oblong, smell unfelt. For the mind in lust of something visceral, it is the equivalent of moving through the D’Orsay with the lights turned off. But it is precisely this that chars the <em>coccinea</em> into the slab of our brains. The rose, as Burne-Jones gazed at it with its hue of crimson and fumes of dreams and songs, overwhelms the reader: too much of sensations drowning us in its decadent cusp. The Cruz de Malta, on the other hand, forces us, not to see, but to see again. It is not a mess of tiny flowers, but a fistful of vigor, multiplied unto itself.\n\nIn the amber afternoon, the crimson and jaune dissipate into the winking eye of the Sun-god but in the torrential afterbirth of the tropical rain, the flower retains its self-same brutality. We confuse the consistency of its form with its <em>ennui</em>, funneling into despise. As a child, I loathed the flower: every garden and yard I played in had it. I studied it as an exercise in horticultural laziness and lack of imagination verging on pornography: the whore of Babylon sports the slut of flowers. It was not until the refinement of vision, and not taste, that I understood that the flower’s beauty is revealed to us by its iconic fidelity: we see the same color, same hue and same tonalities regardless of place, position or politics and yet we cast it out of our gaze for