.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(295,2,'2012-08-31 20:17:52','2012-08-31 20:17:52','Psych-rock is an iffy matter, and even more problematic term to determine music. After all, it is all too easy to go tripping but not as easy to translate such an aesthetic/hermetic experience into something meaningful and beautiful. Usually one ends up confusing hour long sound collages of cats for a good idea, but if there is any band aware of the parameters and possibilities of the genre, it is definitely Fantasmes. Island wunderduo Mario Negrón and Darío Morales Collazo have been at concocting mind-expanding sonic tonics for a while now and their latest release<em> Redness Moon</em> (Last Bummer Records) is a gem of phantasmagoric proportion that will clasp the listener close to its massive ocean swirl of head altering noise.\r\n\r\nThe distant shimmer of a reverb-drenched guitar breathes in, soon doubled by an open bass and a spacious drum. A voice comes in, meshing with the atmosphere, carrying memories of endless bluffs and jewels of hanging clouds: it is the fullness of wind.  The song dissipates, but promptly returns with a slight acoustic reprise before morphing in the mantric groove of the album’s title track. “Redness Moon,” pipes a clarion call of pulsating drums and a tight weave of guitars presaging an oncoming argosy, a threat not yet understood, a threat that doesn’t arrive until the fuzz fizzles and cascades into “Play It Wrong”,<strong> </strong>a full frontaol riff assault with a mondo groove, reminiscent of the Velvets’ “The Gift.” The massive guitars and blasting drums might suggest a straightforward rocker, but the looming and slightly odd minor percussion, meandering piano and   buried background reading betray a more surrealistic happening in the mix. The haze of a heavy movement clears and we’re left with “Dance in the Shadows,” a tender séance that mediates ethereal voicings with the grounded jangle of strings. “Passages” remains faithful to its moniker with a background of distorted ripples that stages the spoken text while providing a welcomed breather before the mammoth “Monster’s Mother,” cretin-like inverted surf stop of Grendel proportion that retreats into an Amon Düül II inspired raga interlude only to come back haunting with one of the most furious drum fills I’ve ever heard committed to tape. The final chapters of the saga seem constituted in a tobacco trance-cum-phantasmagoric-cowpoke-nuance of “Today is Still” and the nine-plus minute psych feature of “Tell Me/ Nothing is Wrong” ranging from spacey phrasing to a whirring drone and back again to a heady Harrison number when acid was in stock and then, almost suddenly, it vanishes.\r\n\r\nProduction-wise, the album is a rare object of tremendous quality. The guitars that chime like bells just as much as a stray thunderbolt and the humongous low-end and walls of drums, tambourines, bells and whistles and other objet trouvés covered by mattresses of washing organs give a round and even sound to the whole experience. Not only do the instruments sound crystalline, they interact and blend with each other marvelously creating a tight knit tapestry. Unlike their predecessor <em>Sidetracked</em> (wait, there’s another Fantasmes review in <a href=\"http://themodernaddendum.blogspot.com/2010/09/fantasmes-sidetracked-haunting-local.html\">Modern Addendum</a>?) with its shoegazing inflections, <em>Redness Moon </em>has a visceral, yet very organic atmosphere. Even when the instruments are treated and tampered, they afford with a natural hum.\r\n\r\nWhat is most gratifying about a record such as this is meticulousness and the variant listening experiences which it affords. It could be regarded as a guitar album à la Television just as much as a drum-driven endeavor. While still indulging in moments of head-splitting psychedelia, the excess of the supposed “anything goes” genre have been limited and carefully measured, not bee: everything is in its right place.\r\n\r\nRedness Moon is an album of displacement and disorientation, of feeling as though one is lingering in a wrong place, of wanting to be or having to arrive at another destination. “I should be there,” sums up the anxiety of embracing change, of wanting to retreat to a known comfort, regardless of its harmful implications. Even its sonic construction with its internal (sonic, though not necessarily conceptual) narrative moving towards a goal suggests and aural pilgrimage with all of its crests and nadirs.  The errant sentiment evoke a constant doubt of not being able to return, and just like its wandering voices, the album trails off exactly like it began, maybe to commence newly again.  And while the violence and oedipal impulses of tracks such as the dominant heteronormative narratives of “Play It Wrong” and “Monster’s Mother,” respectively, scratch the surface of much more complex themes, it does not dwell on them for fear of distracting the whole journey from its end.\r\n\r\n<em>Redness Moon</em>, with its Cormac McCarthyism, its hyptonic grooves and its audio <em>aspecta medusa</em> one would be hard pressed to not be lured into the rituals of the album. It is an album that moves between strange rooms, from the gem-like wonder of shimmering numbers that cut through its haze to the more haphazard eruptions, all the while carefully balancing and managing its mammoth weight.  If the art of crafting an album has been in steady decline, Fantasmes has proven to be one of its opposing stalwarts. It might not be a record that goes everywhere it can, but it goes where it should be.\r\n\r\nYou can get your vinyl copy of Redness Moon <a href=\"http://shop.lastbummerrecords.com/products/fantasmes-redness-moon-lp-pre-order\">here</a>!','The Strange Rooms of Fantasmes’ Redness Moon.','Psych-rock is an iffy matter, and even more problematic term to determine music. After all, it is all too easy to go tripping but not as easy to translate such an aesthetic/hermetic experience into something meaningful and beautiful. ','publish','open','open','','the-strange-rooms-of-fantasmes-redness-moon','','','2012-08-31 20:17:52','2012-08-31 20:17:52','',0,'http://modernaddendum.com/?p=295',0,'post','',0),(296,2,'2012-08-31 20:17:23','2012-08-31 20:17:23','','redness','','inherit','open','open','','redness','','','2012-08-31 20:17:23','2012-08-31 20:17:23','',295,'http://modernaddendum.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/redness.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(297,2,'2012-08-31 20:16:04','2012-08-31 20:16:04','Psych-rock is an iffy matter, and even more problematic term to determine music. After all, it is all too easy to go tripping but not as easy to translate such an aesthetic/hermetic experience into something meaningful and beautiful. Usually one ends up confusing hour long sound collages of cats for a good idea, but if there is any band aware of the parameters and possibilities of the genre, it is definitely Fantasmes. Island wunderduo Mario Negrón and Darío Morales Collazo have been at concocting mind-expanding sonic tonics for a while now and their latest release<em> Redness Moon</em> (Last Bummer Records) is a gem of phantasmagoric proportion that will clasp the listener close to its massive ocean swirl of head altering noise.\n\nThe distant shimmer of a reverb-drenched guitar breathes in, soon doubled by an open bass and a spacious drum. A voice comes in, meshing with the atmosphere, carrying memories of endless bluffs and jewels of hanging clouds: it is the fullness of wind.  The song dissipates, but promptly returns with a slight acoustic reprise before morphing in the mantric groove of the album’s title track. “Redness Moon,” pipes a clarion call of pulsating drums and a tight weave of guitars presaging an oncoming argosy, a threat not yet understood, a threat that doesn’t arrive until the fuzz fizzles and cascades into “Play It Wrong”,<strong> </strong>a full frontaol riff assault with a mondo groove, reminiscent of the Velvets’ “The Gif