e itself to the mental motion, as a well-trained hand can follow on the tracing-paper the outline of an original drawing below it.\r\n-Walter Pater, “Dante Gabriel Rossetti,” <i>Appreciations</i></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 120px;\"></p>\r\n\r\nHers is a face from many dreams. She stares as though her mind was caught in a reverie of the past, yet her body is weighed unto this world. Her song echoes between the tones of oblivion and memory; it is a song only the dead can hear. Her name was Alexa Wilding, a young Victorian woman with aspirations to the theatrical world. In her, Dante Gabriel Rossetti saw a woman worthy of the label “stunner,” but this is a type of unrealized beauty. Once he drew her face unto the canvas, he saw the intemperate corners of this world peel to reveal an ideated realm. She is as an image submerged in water: we do not see the image despite the water obscuring our view but rather through it.\r\nShe no longer is Alexa, a dressmaker from Surrey, she is transformed into a vision of beauty and mourning. She is <i>The Roman Widow</i> (1873) and she hangs in the Pre-Raphaelite wing of the Museo de Arte de Ponce, Puerto Rico. This is the type of painting that dominated Rossetti’s creative phase between 1860’s and 1870’s before the apparition of Jane Burden as idée fixée: it is an allegorical representation, fashioned in the<b> </b>Venetian style, of an idea made manifest through the work of art. She is mourning the death of her husband in his deathly bower. Her hands fall on the strings of a double lute, and in the corner the urn with the remains of her husband hangs wreathed with a throng of roses and strung with the girdle of their marriage. The inscription on the urn reads:\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left; padding-left: 150px;\">DIS MANIBUS\r\nL.AELIO AQUINO\r\nMARITO CARISSIMO\r\nPAPRIA GEMINA\r\nFECIT\r\nAVE DOMINE. VALE DOMINE</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left; padding-left: 150px;\">(To the deities of the underworld: Papiria Gemina\r\nhas made this for her dearest husband Lucius Aelius Aquinas:\r\nhail master, and farewell, master.)</p>\r\nThe function of the text is simple: it creates a context to make the picture and all of its elements cogent. The flowers represent eternal love and her girdle signifies transcendental devotion. There is yet a more complex reading of the picture and text to be explored. The body of the woman is inscribed with semantic signifiers just as the urn is: her ashen skin suggests the deathly pallor of a corpse while her stiff neck can be easily mistaken for an advanced stage of <i>rigor mortis. </i>It is as though the woman herself, and not the song or memorial gifts, that stands as cenotaph of the husband’s memory. She becomes involved in a sacred death ritual, in which her own body is the inscribed epitaph and the painting the gift to her husband’s death bower. As unimportant as the text might seem, it is a crucial component of the painting as a double work of art, since it is imagining a closer relation between image and word.\r\n<i>The Roman Widow</i> stands as a metaphor for Rossetti’s goals for the double work of art. Foremost, the pairing of poetry/text with image is one based more on practicality than poetic realism. The text elucidates or contextualizes the scene of the painting just as the image is meant to illustrate an idea or narrative and symbolic scene (as is the case for Lady Lilith/ “Body’s Beauty” and <i>The Roman Widow</i>). The association of arts also reveals the mutual symbolic structures executed through each medium. As in <i>Girlhood of Mary Virgin</i>, there are two symbolic orders (that of the poem and that of the painting) but both are intertwined to create a totalizing signifying order that brings both pieces together.\r\n<p align=\"center\">…</p>\r\n            As obscure as Rossetti’s poetic language and esoteric symbolism often are<b>, </b>he sympathizes with the reader/viewer’s position as outsider. Just as the “Sonnets for Pictures,” and “Mary’s Childhood” poem prove, the poetic speaker is attempting to mitigate a purely sensual and intellectual abstract experience between the work of art and subject. The poems should be considered as personal interpretations upon a subject, a critical opinion meant to help the audience arrive at their own conclusion and enact their own aesthetic judgments. This is where Rossetti breaks from the Romantic tradition of poetry. Keats’ “Ode on a Grecian Urn” was not meant to convince the reader, it was meant to assert the poet’s subjectivity and personality through the poetic work: the purpose is the realization of the aesthetic process. Rossetti, on the other hand, is concerned with incorporating the literary (and artistic) audience into a critical debate in the<b> </b>development of art and the literature of art in the 19<sup>th</sup> century.\r\nThe “Sonnets for Pictures” chronicles a fundamentally modernist experience. Rossetti engaged these works of art not in a private collection, but in a museum. The Victorian age was witness to a cultural revolution in which gallery visits and trips to the museum were incorporated into<b> </b>the rituals of social life.  The attendance of the Great Exhibition of 1851, a World’s Fair which gathered the latest in industrial technology and the beaux-arts,  is a testament to the rise of culture-capitalism in Victorian England. 2,500 tickets ( at a median price of one shilling or £4.35 by today’s standards) were printed for the opening day, all of which were bought.  Rossetti’s poems are participating in a social statement where the experience of art is no longer private, but public. He approaches<b> </b>these paintings not as an artist, but as member of society with an acute sensibility to what art had to say. Rossetti’s sequence functions as a social statement in the context of Victorian culture and the rise of a literary and artistic audience.\r\nRossetti is very much aware that the double work of art as a medium is a statement in itself. William Michael Rossetti notes that one of the Pre-Raphaelites’ goals was “to have genuine ideas to express.” (xxii) . Part of the circle’s ideological project was to respond to the perceived “stagnancy” of cultural affairs in public circles. Thematically, Rossetti had explored a variety of allegorical themes but he focused more on the <i>how</i> he was to present these ideas, rather than <i>what</i> he was to present. The double work of art poses a riddle that is already implicit to art: how are we to approach this new medium? Furthermore, how are we to approach art and poetry after considering said medium? In this sense, Rossetti was attempting to subvert traditional aesthetic and interpretative judgments on art and poetry. In the art world of Victorian England, the Royal Academy was the public arbiter of taste and aesthetics since its founding<b> i</b>n 1768 and dictated how to judge a work of art based on its historical, heroic and biblical values. Popular tastes in art during the late 18<sup>th</sup> and early 19<sup>th</sup> century focused on the “inventiveness” of narrative scenes rather than their execution (Color, for example, did not figure highly in the “enjoyment” of a picture. It was meant to “fill in the space”).  In the literary world, despite the publication of poets such as Blake, Shelley, and Keats these figures remained relatively unknown. Blake published both  <i>The Songs of Innocence</i> and <i>The Book of Thel</i> in 1789, Shelley published his <i>Alastor</i> and <i>Adonais</i> in 1816 and 1821 respectively, and Keats published <i>Endymion</i> in 1818.  Rossetti’s visual art started out as archaic and medieval and his poetry rang with fundamentally Italian tones. The combination of both disciplines became a manifestation of wanting to change, not only popular tastes, but general social conceptions of art. Millais and Hunt might have contributed works of genius such as <i>Ophelia</i> and <i>The Awakening Conscience</i>, but the double work of art is the fundamentally original Pre-Raphaelite contribution to 19<sup>th</sup> century art and poetry.\r\n\r\nStudying the progress and development of the double work of art is perhaps the most appropriate form of engaging Rossetti’s <i>oeuvre</i>. Walter Pater was not mistaken in asserting that, while Rossetti might not be the poetic voice that sounds the loudest in the development of then-modern poetry, he is certainly the most imaginative and original bard of his generation. His artistic development spans a very wide and complex spectrum: beginning with a consciously antiquated style and evolving towards a dream-like allegorical aesthetic that predates the Symbolist movement in late nineteenth-century Europe. This artistic development cannot be reduced to a refinement of his literary and visual rhetoric for it reveals a profound conceptual understanding of the limits of each art. His early phase is a testament to an ambitious intellectual program. For example, his “Sonnets for Pictures” equate the aesthetic experience of art with a visionary and transcendental connection with an ideal world as his “For a Venetian Pastoral” asserts at its final line: “Life touching lips with Immortality.” (14) In his <i>Girlhood</i> double work, the<b> </b>poem and painting (and its symbolic glossary) functions as dynamic interpretative fields. In the former example, he asserts an ideal world hiding behind a coded world of sensual signs, while in the latter he is betraying truth, asserting that there is only an arbitrary rubric of signs suggesting a world behind it. We should not consider these opposing truths as contradictory or paradoxical, but as complementary ideas that form Rossetti’s fundamental brainwork.\r\n\r\nThis free exploration of various contradictory elements through one harmonic totalizing conception of art and poetry is the core of Rossetti’s double work of art. It allows the poet and painter a new language in which he can recast in new imaginative forms